<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Whole Tree Utilization" class="currentChild" href="Whole_Tree_Utilization">Whole Tree Utilization</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A concept of <a title="Pulp" href="Pulp">pulp</a> making in which an entire tree is cut at ground level and its entire trunk (bark and all), branches, and foliage are all converted into wood chips for use in <a title="Pulping" href="Pulping">pulping</a>. This provides a more economical use of wood, and helps reduce the pressure on future paper fiber suppliers. As new innovations make it easier to remove the contaminants and undesirable materials from whole-tree-based pulp, whole tree utilization is becoming more and more practical as an effective source of <a title="Pulpwood" href="Pulpwood">pulpwood</a>. Other materials, such as waste from sawmills and lumber yards, as well as the use of <a title="Recycled Paper" href="Recycled_Paper">recycled paper</a> is reducing the need for <a title="Virgin Fiber" href="Virgin_Fiber">virgin fiber</a>. 
</p>
